It might be just as well if you are discussing the matter with the Attorney General, you might take up with him the necessity of an act ofParlia- merit to put this Convention out of existence. In any event, even assuming that its work is done, it is still a Convention by statute. What is there on the statute book to say that it does not exist any more? Mr. Chairman, in moving the motion which appears under my name on the order paper this afternoon, I would remind you once again of the terms of reference under which this Convention is constituted, and in particular section 3, which

makes it necessary for this Convention to recom» mend forms of government. My own inclination in the matter, would be to recommend one form of government only, namely responsible govem- ment, but to conform to our terms of reference under the Convention Act it is necessary to recommendfomrs of government. Therefore this resolution means, if it passes, that two forms of government will be recommended to His Majesty’s Government to be put before the people at a national referendum.
